  "text": "Django's session framework implements session key rotation during login via the `cycle_key()` method (SessionBase.cycle_key, django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py:428-437). This method is called to prevent session fixation attacks by creating a new session while preserving the user's data.\n\nThe key rotation flow is: (1) cycle_key() calls create(), (2) create() in SessionStore (django/contrib/sessions/backends/db.py:68-79) implements a retry loop to handle collisions, (3) the loop calls _get_new_session_key() (SessionBase._get_new_session_key, django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py:194-199) to generate a random 32-character key, (4) then calls save(must_create=True) to persist the new session.\n\nCollision handling exists but has both strengths and weaknesses:\n\nWEAKNESS (TOCTOU vulnerability): _get_new_session_key() checks if the key exists (line 198: `if not self.exists(session_key)`) and returns it, but the actual database INSERT happens later in save(). Between the existence check and the INSERT, another concurrent request could insert the same key, creating a race condition.\n\nMITIGATION (Database-level protection): The SessionStore.save() method (lines 114-137) provides actual collision handling through the database: (1) It uses force_insert=True when must_create=True (line 128), which generates SQL INSERT (not UPDATE). (2) The Session model has session_key as a PRIMARY KEY (django/contrib/sessions/base_session.py:28), enforcing uniqueness at the database level. (3) When an IntegrityError is raised due to key collision, save() catches it (lines 130-132) and raises CreateError. (4) The create() loop catches CreateError and retries with a new key (lines 75-77), implementing exponential backoff through repeated _get_new_session_key() calls.\n\nConclusion: While a TOCTOU vulnerability exists at the application level in _get_new_session_key(), the database PRIMARY KEY constraint and the retry logic in create() prevent actual session key collisions. Concurrent requests will never share a session key—if a collision is detected by the database, the create() method retries with a new key. However, the application-level check in _get_new_session_key() is theoretically unnecessary and could be removed in favor of relying solely on database constraints for collision detection."
}

